2026-04-21 01:28:06 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power supply module internal wiring between battery holder, LED branch, and output rails'] hypothesis_explanation='The replacement battery is good at 12 V open circuit, but when inserted the PSU output shows only ~0.012 V, and the LED branch also has ~0 V. Measurements indicate a polarity inversion: the battery positive terminal is effectively tied to the LED/resistor negative node, with the LED’s positive side near 0 V. Continuity of the output cables is normal and there is no polarity inversion between PSU and control module cables. This points to an internal miswiring or reversed connection inside the PSU module between the battery holder and the internal 12 V/0 V rails (and hence the LED branch), so the source is effectively shorted or reverse-biased internally, collapsing the output voltage. Repairing/re-wiring these internal connections to restore correct polarity from the battery to the PSU rails should restore proper 12 V output; remaining modules can then be re-tested if further faults exist.'
